type="user">jms-00EY</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00EY.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Experimental support for objects">Experimental support for objects</fr:title><fr:taxon>Feature</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>To facilitate the development of extensible macro libraries for diagramming and other tasks, <fr:link
href="jms-00CW.xml"
title="Forester 3.0"
addr="jms-00CW"
type="local">Forester 3.0</fr:link> introduces experimental support for <fr:em>objects</fr:em> — which should be thought of as combination of records/structs, closures, and general recursion. An object is created like so:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\my-object{
  \object[self]{
    [method1]{
      the implementation of this method
    }
    [method2]{
      the implementation of another method
      \self#method1
    }
  }
}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>The variable <fr:code>self</fr:code> is explicitly bound, and can be bound to any name you like. Methods currently are not allowed to take any arguments, but this may change in the future. A primitive form of inheritance is supported, using <fr:code><![CDATA[\patch]]></fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\patch{\my-object}[self]{
  [method1]{
    \self/super#method1
    some further code
  }
}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>The support for objects in <fr:link
href="jms-00CW.xml"
title="Forester 3.0"
addr="jms-00CW"
type="local">Forester 3.0</fr:link> is extremely experimental and preliminary: users are discouraged from relying on it.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
